04265nam a22005775i 9780520382398DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203823987 a10.1525/97805203823982doi  a(DE-B1597)566923  a(OCoLC)1178868056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0550002bisacsh1 aPhilliou, Christine M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTurkey :bA Past Against History /cChristine M. Philliou. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration -- tTimeline -- tIntroduction -- t1. Against Power? (1888–1909) -- t2. The Contradictions of Ottoman Constitutionalism and the Remaking of Muhalefet (1908–1913) -- t3. The Joke (1913–1918) -- t4. The True Face of Istanbul (1918–1922) -- t5. Muhalefet from Abroad (1922–1927) -- t6. There Is a World Underground (1928–1945) -- t7. Muhalefet in the Free World (1945–1965) -- tEpilogue -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its earliest days, the dominant history of the Turkish Republic has been one of national self-determination and secular democratic modernization. The story insisted on total rupture between the Ottoman Empire and the modern Turkish state and on the absolute unity of the Turkish nation. In recent years, this hermetic division has begun to erode, but as the old consensus collapses, new histories and accounts of political authority have been slow to take its place. In this richly detailed alternative history, Christine M. Philliou focuses on the notion of political opposition and dissent—muhalefet—to connect the Ottoman and Turkish periods. Taking the perennial dissident Refik Halid Karay as a subject, guide, and interlocutor, she traces the fissures within the Ottoman and the modern Turkish elite that bridged the transition. Exploring Karay’s political and literary writings across four regimes and two stints in exile, Philliou upends the official history of Turkey and offers new dimensions to our understanding of its political authority and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical culturezTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520382398?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520382398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520382398/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021